{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The ECD's broad safe harbor exemptions also granted platforms expansive discretion in setting inconsistent, opaque content rules interpreted as permitting removal of legal speech despite due process gaps [102].",
    "And self-regulatory reliance critically meant limited transparency, evidentiary burdens or accountability around algorithmic amplification of illegal and emotionally charged polarizing content [170].",
    "Thereby the ECD arguably established conditions allowing contemporary disinformation ecosystems exploiting psychological biases to emerge through selective virality-maximizing curation without recourse.The 2018 EU Code of Practice on Disinformation (CPD) represented a first acknowledgment of previous regulatory failures, attempting to secure voluntary commitments from prominent platforms including Facebook, X (Twitter), and Google to limit coordinated influence operations through fact-checking partnerships, content demotion and demonetization [46].",
    "Introduced as a bid to combat fake news amidst the upcoming 2019 European Parliament elections, the Code was an important first step in aligning different stakeholders to set standards on fighting disinformation.",
    "Yet, its non-binding nature and processes beholden to commercial viability attracted extensive critiques [30,34,48]."
  ],
